{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Xw821aPECsyu4wjtLtxDfJ","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Clerk Setup Guide\n     2→\n     3→This guide covers the setup and configuration of Clerk features used in this starter template.\n     4→\n     5→## Clerk Scopes Required\n     6→\n     7→- **Authentication** - User sign-in/sign-up and session management\n     8→- **Organizations** - Multi-tenant workspace management (see setup below)\n     9→- **Billing** - Organization-level subscription management (see setup below)\n    10→\n    11→## Clerk Organizations Setup (Workspaces & Teams)\n    12→\n    13→This starter kit includes multi-tenant workspace management powered by **Clerk Organizations**. To enable this feature:\n    14→\n    15→### Enable Organizations in Clerk Dashboard:\n    16→\n    17→1. Go to [Clerk Dashboard](https://dashboard.clerk.com)\n    18→2. Navigate to **configure**\n    19→3. Click **Organizations settings**\n    20→4. Configure default roles if needed in the roles and permissions.\n    21→\n    22→### Server-Side Permission Checks:\n    23→\n    24→- This starter follows [Clerk's recommended patterns](https://clerk.com/blog/how-to-build-multitenant-authentication-with-clerk)\n    25→\n    26→### Navigation RBAC System:\n    27→\n    28→- Fully client-side navigation filtering using `useNav` hook\n    29→- Supports `requireOrg`, `permission`, and `role` checks (all client-side, instant)\n    30→- Configured in `src/config/nav-config.ts` with `access` properties\n    31→- See `docs/nav-rbac.md` for detailed documentation\n    32→\n    33→### For more information, see:\n    34→\n    35→- [Clerk Organizations documentation](https://clerk.com/docs/organizations/overview)\n    36→- [Multi-tenant authentication guide](https://clerk.com/blog/how-to-build-multitenant-authentication-with-clerk)\n    37→\n    38→## Clerk Billing Setup (Organization Subscriptions)\n    39→\n    40→This starter kit includes **Clerk Billing for B2B** to manage organization-level subscriptions. Plans and features are managed through the Clerk Dashboard, and the application checks access using Clerk's `has()` function.\n    41→\n    42→> [!WARNING]\n    43→> Billing is currently in Beta and its APIs are experimental and may undergo breaking changes. To mitigate potential disruptions, we recommend pinning your SDK and `clerk-js` package versions.\n    44→\n    45→### Key Features:\n    46→\n    47→- Organization-level subscription management\n    48→- Plan-based access control using `<Protect>` component\n    49→- Feature-based authorization\n    50→- Integrated Stripe payment processing\n    51→- Server-side plan/feature checks using `has()` function\n    52→\n    53→### Billing Cost Structure:\n    54→\n    55→Clerk Billing costs **0.7% per transaction**, plus transaction fees which are paid directly to Stripe. Clerk Billing is **not** the same as Stripe Billing. Plans and pricing are managed directly through the Clerk Dashboard and won't sync with your existing Stripe products or plans. Clerk uses Stripe **only** for payment processing, so you don't need to set up Stripe Billing.\n    56→\n    57→### Setup Instructions:\n    58→\n    59→#### 1. Enable Billing:\n    60→\n    61→- Navigate to [Billing Settings](https://dashboard.clerk.com/~/billing/settings) in the Clerk Dashboard\n    62→- Enable billing for your application\n    63→- Choose payment gateway:\n    64→  - **Clerk development gateway**: A shared **test** Stripe account for development instances. This allows developers to test and build Billing flows **in development** without needing to create and configure a Stripe account.\n    65→  - **Stripe account**: Use your own Stripe account for production. **A Stripe account created for a development instance cannot be used for production**. You will need to create a separate Stripe account for your production environment.\n    66→\n    67→#### 2. Create Plans:\n    68→\n    69→- Navigate to [Plans page](https://dashboard.clerk.com/~/billing/plans) in the Clerk Dashboard\n    70→- Select **Plans for Organizations** tab\n    71→- Click **Add Plan** and create plans (e.g., `free`, `pro`, `team`)\n    72→- Set pricing and billing intervals\n    73→- Toggle **Publicly available** to show in `<PricingTable />` and `<OrganizationProfile />` components\n    74→\n    75→#### 3. Add Features to Plans:\n    76→\n    77→- You can add Features when creating a Plan, or add them later:\n    78→  1. Navigate to the [Plans](https://dashboard.clerk.com/~/billing/plans) page\n    79→  2. Select the Plan you'd like to add a Feature to\n    80→  3. In the **Features** section, select **Add Feature**\n    81→- Feature names in Clerk Dashboard should match what you check in code\n    82→\n    83→#### 4. Usage in Code:\n    84→\n    85→**Server-side checks using `has()`:**\n    86→\n    87→```typescript\n    88→// Check if organization has a Plan\n    89→const hasPremiumAccess = has({ plan: 'gold' });\n    90→\n    91→// Check if organization has a Feature\n    92→const hasPremiumAccess = has({ feature: 'widgets' });\n    93→```\n    94→\n    95→The `has()` method is available on the auth object and checks if the Organization has been granted a specific type of access control (Role, Permission, Feature, or Plan) and returns a boolean value.\n    96→\n    97→**Client-side protection using `<Protect>`:**\n    98→\n    99→```tsx\n   100→<Protect\n   101→  plan='bronze'\n   102→  fallback={<p>Only subscribers to the Bronze plan can access this content.</p>}\n   103→>\n   104→  <h1>Exclusive Bronze Content</h1>\n   105→</Protect>\n   106→```\n   107→\n   108→Or protect by Feature:\n   109→\n   110→```tsx\n   111→<Protect\n   112→  feature='premium_access'\n   113→  fallback={<p>Only subscribers with the Premium Access feature can access this content.</p>}\n   114→>\n   115→  <h1>Exclusive Premium Content</h1>\n   116→</Protect>\n   117→```\n   118→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_0133G6eTKKyED961Dh5CjooQ","session_id":"b1ad336c-66a2-4f3f-98dd-2e5d8c4f5736","uuid":"c6e44df6-f2c9-4cba-84ee-4c3dbf4aac9f"}
